The maximum quantity of propane and butane that can be stored at the facility is 45,000 pounds.

2.4 General Accidental Release Prevention Program and Chemical-Specific Prevention 

The EPA risk management regulations identify three levels of requirements.  Program Level 2 applies to the Facility, because this facility is not subject to the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), Process Safety Management program and does not qualify for Program Level 1.  The facility has procedures in place to prevent and mitigate potential releases of toxic and flammable substances including propane and butane.  These procedures are detailed in the Facility's RCRA Part B hazardous waste permit.  The procedures include, but are not limited to, the following:

A?    An inspection program, which requires daily, weekly, monthly and annual inspections of process equipment, alarm systems, and management practices, with a procedure for documenting and correcting any deficiencies identified in inspections;

A?    A standard operating procedure for the transfer of flammable and combustible liquids;

A?    A standard operating procedure for ensuring that incompatible materials are not consolidated together;

A?    A waste analysis plan which ensures that the waste received by the Facility conforms to the waste as initially represented by each generator, and that each waste stream is managed correctly;

A?    A security plan to prevent unknowing or unwanted access to the facility; and

A?    A training plan which ensures that employees at the facility are adequately trained to perform the

ir job duties knowledgeably and safely.

In addition, the Facility has instituted a Program Level 2 prevention program consisting of the following elements:

A?    Process Safety Information including Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) for regulated substances;

A?    Process Hazard Analysis, including a systematic evaluation of potential hazards associated with handling regulated substances and development of recommendations for improving safety;

A?    Operating procedures regarding transfer, storage and processing of regulated substances;

A?    Training of workers on operating procedures;

A?    Maintenance procedures to ensure mechanical integrity of equipment;

A?    Compliance audits of the prevention program to be conducted every three years; and

A?    Incident investigation to document releases and accidents of regulated substances.

2.5 Five-year Accident History

During the past five (5) years (April 2010 to May 2015), there has not been any accident involving any RMP regulated substance that qualifies for reporting under 40 CFR Part 68.  

2.6 Emergency Response Program

It is the policy of the Facility to place the highest priority on employee safety and health and on protection of the community from all plant-induced environmental conditions.  An emergency response plan has been developed which prescribes emergency procedures, which the facility will implement in the event of a release or fire at the facility.

The Facility's Emergency Response Plan is identified as the facility Contingency Plan.  The purpose of this plan is to describe both the hazards associated with the management of waste materials at the facility and the steps that will be taken to minimize the risk associated with each hazard.  By ensuring that proper preventative measures are taken at all times and by providing for emergency response procedures to be followed in the event of any unexpected occurrence(s), the Facility intends to operate its facility in a manner that does not pose a significant threat
